---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="About" description="About The Grimoire Index — methodology and editorial policy.">
  <article class="max-w-2xl prose-content">
    <h1 class="text-3xl mb-6">About</h1>

    <p>
      The Grimoire Index is a reference catalog of magic systems in fiction. Each entry analyzes how a system
      works — its mechanics, its costs, who can use it, and how it functions in its story — and tags the system
      across six independent taxonomy facets so it can be found by mechanism rather than just by name.
    </p>

    <h2>Why this exists</h2>
    <p>
      Magic systems are one of the most discussed elements of speculative fiction, but no comprehensive,
      cross-franchise reference catalogs them in a structured way. Existing fan wikis cover individual universes
      in depth; what's missing is a place to ask "show me every magic system with reciprocal-cost mechanics" or
      "what's the equivalent of Sanderson's hard-magic approach in TTRPGs."
    </p>

    <h2>Editorial policy</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Original analysis only.</strong> Entries are written in our own words. We do not reproduce source
        text, lyrics, or extended quotes.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Mechanism over mythology.</strong> If a fictional world calls its magic "divine gifts" but
        mechanically it's an inherited genetic trait, it gets tagged as both. Tags reflect how the system
        functions, not how its world describes it.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Spoiler discipline.</strong> Core mechanics are not spoilers. Plot reveals tied to a magic
        system's nature are flagged when present.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Encyclopedic tone.</strong> We describe and analyze; we don't rank or rate. A system can be
        called "unusual" or "notably constrained" but never "the best."
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Designer commentary is cited.</strong> When a creator has publicly discussed their design
        choices, we reference that with attribution.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The taxonomy</h2>
    <p>
      We use six independent facets: <a href="/taxonomy">Systematization</a>, Source of Power, Cost Structure,
      Scope of Effect, Narrative Function, and Practitioner Demographics. They are independent, not
      hierarchical — most systems carry multiple tags within several facets.
    </p>

    <h2>Suggesting a system</h2>
    <p>
      Have a magic system we should add? Email <a href="mailto:hello@grimoire-index.example">hello@grimoire-index.example</a>{' '}
      with the system name, the work it appears in, and a sentence on why it's interesting.
    </p>
  </article>
</Layout>

